{{refimprove|date=July 2017}} {{Infobox court case |name = R v Mubila |court = Southern Rhodesia, Bulawayo |image = |imagesize = |imagelink = |imagealt = |caption = |full name = R v Mubila |date decided = {{Start date|1955|08|17|df=y}} |citations = 1956 (1) SA 31 (SR) |transcripts = |judges = Beadle J and assessors |number of judges = 1 |decision by = Beadle J |prior actions = |appealed from = |appealed to = |subsequent actions = |related actions = |opinions = |keywords = Criminal law, Murder, Causation, Novus actus interveniens, Proximate cause |italic title = force }}
'''''R v Mubila''''' is an important case in South African and Zimbabwean criminal law, heard on August 17, 1955, in which the accused was charged with murder. DP McCormac appeared for the Crown, and John Morris for the accused.
Its significance lies particularly in the area of [[Causation (law)|legal causation]]. The court expressed negatively the idea of a proximate cause, with the statement that there must be no ''[[Breaking the chain|novus actus interveniens]]'' between X's conduct and Y's death; it also expressed it positively, in the contention that Y's death must follow directly from X's conduct.
The court held that, when a complainant has been injured as the result of an [[assault]] upon him, he has no obligation to obtain medical assistance to alleviate the gravity of the wound. Nor is there any obligation on him to follow rigidly all the advice given him by his medical advisers if he does seek that assistance. Provided that, in disregarding that advice, he does not introduce some new danger which would not have existed had the advice never been taken at all, his failure to follow that advice cannot be a factor which can avail the accused in any argument that the original injury was not the cause of death.
== See also == * [[South African criminal law]]
== References == * ''R v Mubila'' 1956 (1) SA 31 (SR).
